These books use mystery and strange events, which are not common in other books from that time. This makes the characters stronger and shows more about what they feel and why they do things.

Here is a part from "Oliver Twist": “And now, many confusing ideas came into his mind. He seemed to walk between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing. He heard their words. When he paid attention, he found he was talking to them. Suddenly, he was shocked by the sound of guns. There were loud cries, lights flashed, and all was loud and chaotic, as some unseen hand took him quickly away. Through all these quick visions, he felt a pain that tired and bothered him all the time.” (Dickens, 220)

In "Oliver Twist," these strange events often show what Oliver feels inside, what hurts him, and what he understands about the things happening around him. In chapter 28, when the shooting is talked about again, Oliver remembers it like a dream, while he looks for help. The part shows that Oliver had no control over what happened and how bad his health had become. He sees Sikes and Crackit in his mind. The shooting takes over his senses, and he does not notice the “unseen hand” that takes him away. He feels his sadness again, without the shock of pain, as the pain is now always there and connected with fear. Since Oliver is overwhelmed, it makes you wonder who caused his trouble, because it was not him. This shows that Oliver cannot control events, even when his life is in danger. It also suggests that Oliver feels more defeated, like old Fagin is starting to break him and make him accept this sadness, affecting how he reacts. Otherwise, we might think that Oliver would try to do something, at least to save his own life.

“The day passed – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its silence and short in its few hours.”

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program. I helped young students with their studies. I was best at English and reading. One teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. Adrian had trouble reading. I noticed something unusual. He could say some letters well, but not others. Adrian was Latino, but he spoke English perfectly. We had a hard time until I met his mother. I was watching a few kids while others were on a field trip. Adrian's mother came in. She did not speak English, only Spanish. I knew a little Spanish, so we talked. Then I understood: Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet well. I hope this helped him. I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story to talk about language problems in schools. This is common in California. It shows that these problems are not always clear. Even children who speak English well can have trouble reading. We all know this problem is real. What can we do? For Adrian, the answer was simple: more help with English reading, letters, and sounds. But for other children who do not speak much English, it is harder. There is no single answer. We need to use many methods: dual language programs, regular classes, private tutors, and ESL classes. We should combine them all.

The dual language system is a good idea. It helps all children, not just those who speak Spanish. Studies show that children in bilingual programs do better in school. Some people fear it wastes resources and does not help most students. But that is wrong. If we use these programs for all, every child will benefit. How do we do this? Should all teachers be bilingual? No. That is not practical. But we can have special helpers or tutors who are bilingual.

From the time we are young, many of us hear that there is something bigger than us. Some learn about it in Sunday school or Temple. Others look inside themselves for answers. Many accept the religion of their parents. Some do not. They say there is nothing beyond what they know. We might choose one belief and then change to another later. Whatever we choose, we try to find a part of ourselves through our own view of spirituality. We look for a light to guide us out of darkness.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, listening to rain on the tin roof and smoked together. The rain filled the gutters and soaked the plants. He looked into the rain, half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner over months, and his clothes hung loose. His hair was thinner too. He looked into the rain and avoided my eyes. I felt alone and scared. I could not tell him I would miss him because it would make it real. I hugged him, sat down, moved my chair closer, and looked into the rain with him.

My father died in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The treatment did not ease his pain. It only kept him alive a few more months. I did not know the value of this when he only suffered longer. I wondered what kind of God would do this. Alone at night, I did not pray. If God was there, I thought, he stopped listening to me long ago.

I did not want to see him pass from this life. So I did not. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. I knew him better than others did, and I knew he would not want me to watch his death. I stayed in bed for three days and waited for news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early supporter of Republicanism. He was mainly a farmer. This work and his short time in politics made him known for strong opinions about personal freedom and government. He believed in a farming system. This idea was the base of his thoughts on government. He wanted to protect and support what he saw as the best job. This belief shaped his views on who should have power, the Constitution, and the courts.

John Taylor thought the United States could build a perfect system. There were no old customs to stop the new government. This allowed for self-rule. He believed in natural rights for all people. He said these rights are linked. If one right is lost, all rights lose value. These rights should not be taken by the government. He said in a "state of nature," strong and clever people win. But in a society, this should not happen.

Taylor believed a good society needs a government. This government should understand the good and bad in people. Taylor had strong ideas about right and wrong. He said government, run by people, will have human virtues and faults. He said good rules protect private property, help farming, and limit capitalism. A government with good rules will be fair, even if leaders are greedy. He thought self-interest drives people. It is bad when it harms others. A good government keeps man's bad side in check. But it must be watched to stop bad rules.

Taylor, like other Republicans of his time, wanted the Constitution to be strictly followed. He wanted a small Federal government. It should only have powers clearly given in the Constitution. He thought a big Federal government costs a lot and could become oppressive. But he also thought a simple reading of the Constitution is risky. Without knowing what the writers meant, it could lead to problems. He saw the Declaration of Independence as the true guide of the United States. It shows the country as states with their own powers, not one single nation.

I looked down. My mind tried to understand what I saw. I did not feel anything. I watched closely but did not connect my thoughts to any deeper ideas. Thoughts came and went quickly. It felt like I had no real thoughts, just a flow of seeing. 

Once, an artist I knew told me to buy a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I wanted to learn to draw since I was six years old. The book teaches about drawing and how the brain sees lines. One idea in the book is to use a square frame around a picture. This makes a big picture, like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen, easy to see as just the bowl of fruit. 

At that moment, I was looking at the bowl in front of me. I could not use the artist's frame in my mind. I was too amazed to do anything but look. Artists like Picasso, Monet, and those from the Italian Renaissance had their styles. If I wanted to call my view Art, then this was the start of my work, my story—Work in Brown. 

I reached for my tool. My hand moved as I wished, ready to create. Water spun around, clear and smooth. Bits of stuff floated away. My hand moved quickly again, hitting the toilet handle. The brown thing stayed, stuck at the bottom of the toilet. 

I held a mop and stood with my feet apart. My green tie felt tight around my neck. I frowned as I looked at the mess someone left in the Rite Aid bathroom. After a few more flushes and quiet moments, I reached for the toilet paper. I wrapped my hand until it looked like an oven mitt. I stood up straight, then bent down. My hand went into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for a turkey.

Young people are dying in car crashes. Many reasons cause this problem for the youngest drivers in America. The National Institutes of Health say one reason is that the teen brain is not ready for the dangers of driving. Also, teens do not have much driving experience. This lack of experience leads to more deadly accidents, car rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.

Teens have more accidents when they drive with friends. They often do this. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center did a study. It showed a link between the age of passengers and the number of traffic accidents.

California and other states have tried to make driving safer for teens. They have rules for temporary licenses. These rules limit the hours teens can drive and do not allow other young people as passengers.

But I think these licenses are only a temporary fix. The real problem is that young drivers, as a group, are not ready to handle driving risks. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman says even 18 is too young for a regular license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman’s research shows young people like to take risks for excitement. So, it might be better to wait until this thrill-seeking is less strong. If we keep giving licenses to young teens, we will see more deadly crashes. Many young people will be driving by 2010.

Making new laws about this would be simple. Schools can offer driving classes, but no one under 18 should drive a car. A temporary permit could be given before a full license, and some practice hours would be needed. The number of hours could be like those in most states. For example, in California, it is now 6 hours of training and 50 hours of practice with an adult. Since the bad statistics for teen drivers are similar in all states, a national law would help protect teens everywhere.

This idea for a law is not new.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short meaning of the disorder. Next, it explains how to know if someone has it, with common signs to watch for. Finally, the paper ends with ways a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is about how well the central nervous system uses what we hear. It means the brain cannot process sounds right. People with CAPD can hear fine, so they are not "hearing impaired." But, the part of the brain that understands what we hear does not work as it should.

The first time people talked about this disorder was in the mid-1950s. It was called "auditory imperception" then. Researchers looked at children with communication problems. In 1954, the Italian team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started making tests for these children. In 1961, Kimura made new tests to understand how the brain works with hearing. In 1977, a big meeting helped start more research on children with CAPD.

CAPD can show in many ways. A person may not know where a sound is coming from. They may have trouble telling the difference between sounds. They may not recognize sound patterns or changes in speech. One sound might block another. They may not understand sound clues or the order of sounds.

To know if someone has CAPD, they must be checked by watching how they listen and respond. This can be done by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others. There is no single test that works for everyone, and no known cause for CAPD. Tests may include asking people to tell apart different sounds and recording responses to signals in the ear.

I want to study social work. I plan to work with the Division of Family and Children Services. I want to help children who have been hurt or ignored. I also want to help families with problems. I can bring these values to social work: service, respect, ethics, and commitment. I want to help people improve their relationships and become better in my job. These values are important to social workers and to me.

I always wanted to help people. But I did not know what job I wanted. In high school and college, I saw people run away from their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. Because of what I saw, I chose to study Psychology. But I still did not know what job to choose. So, after I finished college in 2009, I took a break. One summer day, I met a friend. She introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy. He was nervous. She said he was there to get away from his abusive parents. The next day, I found out he called the police to his parents’ home. I went to his parents' house to see if I could help. I talked to the police and told them about my degree in Psychology. The police asked me to speak to the parents. The law could not help the boy. I talked to the parents. They seemed nervous. They made excuses and said their son was lying. After this, I thought more about a job in social work. I want to help children with family problems.

Social justice is also important in social work. We say each person is important, but we still want everyone to be the same. I think it is better to be different. In high school and college, I stood against social injustice. I dyed my hair different colors. I wore clothes that showed who I am. I pierced my ears more than usual. I joined GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance). I fought against racism and discrimination when I saw it. I believe in social justice. I will keep fighting against social injustice.

This paper looks at the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to insomnia. The biological model studies genes that are passed down and medical parts of health. The Sociocultural model looks at how environment relates to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review on insomnia talks about these models and explains each study chosen to help understand the models. The research findings are then examined to show their strong and weak points.

A sleep disorder can be a primary sleep disorder, a disorder linked to another mental disorder, or a disorder linked to other problems. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are linked to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other sleep disorders can be due to medical issues or substance use. Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia is a problem with getting or staying asleep, while Primary Hypersomnia is trouble staying awake, both for at least one month. Narcolepsy includes cataplexy and/or automatic REM. Dyssomnias focus on starting and staying asleep, while Parasomnias are related to unusual behaviors or physical happenings during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep problems due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review focuses on insomnia and primary sleep disorders in relation to biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physical aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus with orexin help control sleep and wakefulness. A study with mice showed that there are GABAB receptors on these neurons that control sleep/wake states. Activating the GABAA receptor helps sleep. If this receptor is stopped from working, it can reduce anxiety and help sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These results suggest that findings from mice can apply to humans. This shows a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. A problem with this receptor could affect a person's ability to sleep well without medicine. The sociocultural meaning of this study is that if the trait was inherited, it could affect sleep. Changing the receptor would disturb sleep, which would negatively affect areas like school, work, and daily activities that need focus.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Moving around campus is a problem for many, including me. In my first year, I lived in a dorm room at East Halls, which is very far east on campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in places like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, which happens often in State College. I talked to an alum not much older than me, who said that not long ago, East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large empty land. Now, that space has sports fields, big new buildings like the new Creamery and health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As our campus grows, moving from one place to another becomes harder. What is the best way to solve this problem? On a college campus, the answer is the bicycle. But just having a bike is not enough. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be made for bikes.

I talked to a friend who started biking again after not doing so for many years. He said he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the best way to get around." Biking is good for your body and it is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many students, I now live off campus, as far from the center as some dorms. The best thing I did this year was to buy a bike. I have class in the Thomas building every day, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast. The only problem is that Pollock Road is the quickest way to Thomas building from my house, and it is not always easy to travel on, even with a bike. Walking has its good points too, but I am too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable way to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes from my day. That’s more than two and a half hours each week. Add all the other time I would spend walking to other classes and appointments. That’s more time than I can afford.

Aldous Huxley talks about the danger of technology and capitalism in his book Brave New World. In the story, people care more about the group than the individual. They are taught to seek quick happiness above all else. The people are controlled by a bigger plan set by the World Controller. When we look at this book with Marxist ideas, we see Huxley's worries about these systems. Words from Marxism like "false consciousness" show that Huxley is talking about problems in the economy of his time.

Capitalism is made fun of with the idea of false consciousness from Marxism. Regular people do not understand their real class relations because they only care about their own gain. This is because of control over workers, shown in how people are taught in Brave New World. The lower classes, like Delta and Gamma, have no real will. They are taught to buy and spend through sleep-teaching. The World Controller uses this to control them. Groups are controlled by other groups. Lower classes do not know they are controlled and support the system of capitalism and consumerism. Higher classes know but do little about it. Only some, like Bernard, question their place. The way social classes interact shows the problems of capitalism.

In Brave New World, there are no real relationships. Characters are not deep, even main ones. Huxley may be saying that technology and capitalism take away free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do strong feelings. Interactions are shallow, with men talking about women’s looks and women talking about their encounters. Each class is happy with their place, showing the effect of capitalism. Their total obedience to their role in society shows Marxist ideas about workers who think they are better as long as they keep consuming and following the rules.

Almost four years ago, I took a course in Islam at CBC. One main topic in the class was if Islam is a hostile religion. This question is even more important today. Since 9/11, I have seen the media change. At first, it showed Islam as hostile. Now, it is very tolerant of Islam in America. I think, in 2001, we could not have a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who has a Muslim background in his family.

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad is interesting to me. What I know about Muhammad's history seems different from the biography. I thought Muhammad forced people to convert to Islam. He would conquer tribes and make them follow Islam. But the biography shows Muhammad as misunderstood and humble. People came to him because they saw truth in his teaching.

There are similarities between Jesus and the miracles of Muhammad. For example, Muhammad took mutton and milk and made it enough for forty men. This writing style makes me think the writers wanted Muhammad to be seen as a humble prophet. This is hard for me because it makes Jesus's life and miracles seem less important. It feels like they take credit for Jesus through Muhammad.

Many stories in the biography try to show how people converted to Islam. But these stories often come from someone who heard it from someone else. This makes the stories seem less true and more suspicious to me.

The biography tries to show Muhammad as a godly, humble, and gentle man. But history shows something else. I wonder if Muslims today know about the true history of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his beliefs were quickly left behind as Christian thought developed after his life. If we look at history, we see Christianity moving away from its start. Today, there is more awareness and a new way of thinking. Some people hold on to old beliefs and resist change, but they may not be enough to affect everyone. Among Christians, knowledge of history will grow a lot in the future. People will want to know what was added to Christianity and what Jesus really wanted. This change may take a long time, but it will happen. Christianity will go back to its original form. A movement will grow, removing added ideas, and going back to what Jesus taught. As this change happens in the United States and Europe, people will worship like in Jesus' time, following only his ideas. The church will stay strong to lead. But, beliefs and practices will become more alike instead of different. Over time, there have been big changes in history. For example, Christians were once hurt by the Roman Empire, but later, the empire became Christian. In our country, we have moved from slavery to leadership for African-Americans. The big change coming will be in the Christian religion, going back to its source, and becoming less diverse. This change will happen by reading Jesus’ words as metaphorical, not literal. So what happened since Jesus’ time? If we look back in history, we find only Judaism, which started Christianity. Belief in one God, a revealed religion, and Hebrew scriptures were all important by the time Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people were not united. They divided into groups like Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and common people.

I think "The Jungle" shows that, deep down, people are naturally greedy and self-centered. They care only about themselves and making their lives better. They do not care about people lower than them. "The Jungle" shows this in many ways. The main example is the owners and managers of big factories. They want to make their companies as big and great as possible. They do not care who or what gets hurt in their way. 

Upton Sinclair describes the pollution from the factories. He writes about big chimneys and smoke going into the sky. Sinclair wants to show the damage from this pollution. He shows that the owners do not care about people or animals who might get hurt. They do not care about the smoke coming from the factories or the waste from the animals. 

The owners and managers also do not care about the workers who make them rich. They do anything to save or make more money. Sinclair writes, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." 

Workers have to work long hours. They might lose their jobs without notice or help. During the time of "The Jungle," there were few laws to protect workers. Managers and owners could do what they wanted. Workers had to work fast and in bad conditions. The book shows that workers had to deal with these bad conditions. There were no groups to help them. Unions were formed, but they often hurt more than they helped because they took money from poor workers. 

Workers were treated so badly that they were like slaves. Sinclair writes, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery." This shows that workers had no escape from the system. They were always close to starvation and depended on cruel men.

"Dream-Land" is a poem by Edgar Allan Poe. Poe thought it was one of his better works. In this poem, he uses the word "Thule" in lines 6 and 56. Mabbott says this word goes back to Virgil. Virgil used "Thule" to mean an island north of Britain. The Greeks thought this was the edge of the known world. But there is a more recent link to this word. Poe liked German writers. This is important because it shows Poe knew about Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt wrote about Poe and Goethe. He said Poe's poem was like Goethe's work. 

The Oxford Companion to English Literature says Goethe was famous for writing the poetic drama Faust. It was published in two parts, in 1808 and 1832. In the second part of Faust, there is a poem called "The King of Thule." This poem is about a king. His wife dies after giving him a goblet. He drinks a lot and cries because he misses her. He decides to die, gives his things to his children, but keeps the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, and dies. The King of Thule and the king in "Dream-Land" are a lot alike. It might show Poe's own feelings of loss.

Poe uses the word "Thule" twice in his writings. He first uses "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." He also uses "Thule" in "Dream-Land." "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as similar works. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about Thule. It is dark and lonely. The speaker sees dead friends and a world without color. In Goethe's poem, the king is also lonely after losing his wife. It feels like the speaker in "Dream-Land" steps into Goethe’s poem.

Goethe was an important writer. Poe likely knew of him. Poe also respected Tennyson. This connection to Tennyson would have led Poe to Goethe’s work. Goethe's work was reproduced many times after it first came out. This is how Poe might have known it.

In California, can a customer who slipped on an applesauce spill in a store get extra money as punishment for the store? The customer must show the manager acted with bad intent. The manager knew about the spill twice but did not clean it for 30 minutes because he was eating dinner.

A judge may not quickly reject Jennifer Palmer's request for extra money. To get this money, Palmer must show the manager's actions were done with a willful disregard for harm. She must also show the actions were very bad. Palmer can argue that Martin, the manager, should have known not cleaning the spill was dangerous. Many people had already slipped in the store in the months before Palmer's accident. Even with this knowledge, Martin did not clean the spill. Palmer's claim that Martin's actions were very bad is less strong. But it is still possible because six slip-and-fall accidents happened in 2009, and Martin did not keep the store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, a worker at D&D Markets, told his manager, Paul Martin, about the applesauce spill. Martin said he was on a dinner break and did not want to deal with it. At 5:15 pm, another worker, Mary J. Haddigan, also told Martin about the spill. Martin gave the same response. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and hurt her back badly. Before Palmer's fall, five other slip-and-fall incidents were reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for money to cover her injury and extra money for punishment. We are thinking about asking the court to reject the request for extra money.

In California, a person can get extra money for punishment if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." The law says malice is when someone intended to cause harm or acted very badly and ignored others' safety. Courts say actions are malicious when the defendant knew the actions were dangerous and still did it. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She always felt like she needed something. This desire could not be satisfied. It started when she was 14, just starting her teenage years. It was still there 3 years later, when she was 17. By now, she thought she wanted someone, not something. But she was not interested in any boys. Some boys liked her and tried to win her heart, but no one interested her. She often asked herself about this strange feeling, trying to find out why she felt this way. She had some ideas, but nothing clear. So she lived her life, always wondering about her desires.

A day at home was usually calm. Her parents were good and quiet people. They did not argue with each other, and they rarely argued with their daughter. They only argued about her wanting to be independent and free. She was the daughter of calm parents, but she had a lively and fun personality. This made her well-liked because she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, trying to find inspiration, she heard a short scream from the kitchen. It was her mother's voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" she asked. She saw her mother on the ground, in pain, saying "Ow" with short breaths. The daughter ran to her and tried to help. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." Her mother's words were rushed and tight, and the daughter knew she was in a lot of pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me how I can help you." Her mother showed her hands, and the daughter was glad she had learned to be strong. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back seat, and drove.

At the hospital, there were smells of disinfectant and sickness, mixed with fear. But she did not notice that, because she was too busy helping her mother. She quickly carried her mother in and called for help. Some worried people came, and someone brought a rolling bed and laid her mother down. They took her to be checked right away, and the daughter sat and waited with worry.

Her mother had fallen off a stool while trying to get a vase from the top cabinet.

This study aims to show that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), shown by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a lower risk of long-term heart disease (CHD) and stroke. The aMed diet is a changed version of the Med diet. It includes eating more plant foods, such as plant proteins, fruits, nuts, whole grains, and beans. It also includes eating more monounsaturated fat (not saturated fat) and fish, and eating less animal products and saturated fats. Drinking alcohol in small amounts is okay.

Earlier studies found that following a Med diet is linked to a lower risk of death from heart disease. One study showed that the Med diet helped people lose weight better than a low-fat diet. It also lowered the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese people. Past studies did not focus on stroke or deaths from stroke.

This study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, who had no history of heart disease or diabetes. They were part of the Nurses' Health Study, which included 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times using "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) to check nutrient intake in the past year. More than 95% of nurses stayed in the study for 20 years. FFQs were checked for accuracy. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by looking at medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. If records were not available, cases were marked "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal heart attacks classified this way. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and hormone use after menopause were calculated for each FFQ. Starting in 1986, physical activity during free time was also checked.

To reduce random differences for a person and better show long-term diet intake, averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two previous years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could affect results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone use after menopause, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to check the link between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using different models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

A higher aMed diet score was linked to a lower risk of new CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up, 2391 new cases of CHD, 1763 new cases of stroke, and 1077 deaths from cardiovascular disease (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women with the highest aMed scores had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those with the lowest scores (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign says that Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, the star of the movie Juno, stands alone on a street corner. She holds a piece of cardboard above her head. The unsettling message is written with a marker on her sign. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. It is controlled by a harsh military group that took power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, there were street protests, the first in ten years. Many Burmese monks led these protests. People called it “The Saffron Revolution,” named for the color of the monks' robes. At first, more people showed interest in the protests. The Burmese government allowed the monks to gather peacefully. But soon the situation became violent. Some saw it as a war between the monks and the military. Soldiers invaded and destroyed monasteries. Foreign reporters were arrested and jailed. A Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, while at a street protest. The official number of deaths is 13. But an army officer, Colonel Hla Win, who left the army, said, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is not new. Governments have wanted to stop protests and keep complete control for a long time. Roman emperors said they were chosen by the gods to rule. Japanese emperors were believed to be gods sent to lead their people. Our current president, George W. Bush, talks every week with Ted Haggard, leader of a group called Stupid People Worldwide.

Some well-known examples of these actions include the 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square. Intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the government. The death count varies. The Chinese government says 200-300 died. The Chinese Red Cross says 2,000-3,000 died. Another example is the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s. Hutu groups, with help from the Rwandan government, killed many Tutsis and political moderates. Hitler’s 'Third Reich' is another extreme example. During that time, many Jewish people were rounded up and killed.

Duke Ellington is important in jazz because he lived a long time and was very creative. He was good at leading his band. On the piano, Ellington was often subtle, but he was great at writing music. He made complex pieces that showed the skills of his band members. Ellington let soloists improvise, and he also wrote pieces that used the special style of his band members. This made the band sound unique and original. He knew how each player sounded and how they fit together in the band. This helped him write some of the best jazz music.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's sound and new ideas. It mentions Creole Love Call, where he used the voice like a jazz instrument. This was an early example of using voice to add color without words. In Creole Love Call, Ellington showed he could match the style of his soloists. This piece is a slow twelve-bar blues with six parts:

1. First part: Voice and reeds call and respond. The voice starts smooth and then gets rough.
2. Second part: Muted trumpet plays the melody with blue notes.
3. Third part: Clarinet solo in high notes, with a soft piano behind it.
4. Fourth part: The full band echoes the first part with brass and reeds.
5. Fifth part: The reeds call and respond in high notes, with brass and rhythm backing.
6. Sixth part: Like the first part, voice and reeds call and respond. The voice uses the “growl” technique.

End: A quick vocal run and a strange trombone ending.

Ellington used voice to add a new sound. This is a style he used often. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington mixed tight writing with tone color. "Bubber" Miley on trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing made a rich sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) shows these ideas more. Ellington used Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton to start the melody on muted trombone.

Why do living things change over time? Are there limits that shape how they change? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that scientists had hardly begun to describe simple living forms using math, and this is still true today. Recently, math models have been used to study how mollusk shells form over time (Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study looks at how math models and experiments can show how and why these changes happen in Prunum. We used X-ray pictures of Prunum to find numbers that help model shell shapes. These numbers were put into a program called CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We made models of shell shapes to see what changes are possible in Prunum. These results are mixed with studies to learn more about big changes over time in this group.

A shell can be seen as a tube that moves through space. The turns of the shell are called whorls, and they spiral around a central line called the columella. The size of whorls can change, and a line called a suture separates each whorl. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one. The spire is all whorls except the last. The top of the spire is the apex, and the other end is the base. The animal comes out of the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from the top, bottom, front, and back. Normally, a shell is viewed from the front, with the opening facing the viewer and the top pointing up.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top and find where the first line begins. Draw a line to divide the shell into two parts. Count whorls from this line, and estimate to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of openings that move as the animal builds its shell. You can trace the path of these openings by using the center, and the size of each opening.

This path can be shown in pictures and math. Once you have a math model, you can change the numbers to see how the shell grows.

The number of babies and young children who die in Indonesia has not changed much in the last ten years. The country is doing well in reaching some goals, like clean water and toilets. But, it is not doing well in making sure mothers and children are healthier. There are many reasons why this is happening. We need to make the health system stronger instead of only making new programs.

Indonesia has made progress with more babies being born with a trained health worker present. Now, 72% of births have a health worker there. But, this number also includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot help if there is a problem during birth. This is why many mothers die from heavy bleeding. So, the progress in this area is not as good as it seems, and more work is needed. Also, fewer children under five with diarrhea see a health worker now. We do not have all the information about care for mothers after birth, but it is a concern too, with low numbers across the country.

Rates of Cesarean sections are still low, around 4%. There is a problem because 7% of these happen in cities but only 2% happen in rural areas. This shows that healthcare services are mainly in cities. Another problem is that poor people use health services much less than rich people. There is a 27% gap between the poorest and richest groups. The poor find it hard to get healthcare, likely because they have to pay out of their own pockets.

To make care for mothers and babies better, we need to think about the best way to fix the problem. Should Indonesia make programs just for this issue, or should it make the whole health system better? Making programs for one specific area can seem like a good idea. These programs have clear goals and can show results faster. But there are problems too. Spending a lot on one program can mean less money for other programs. People may leave other areas to work where there is more money, like happened with funding for HIV/AIDS affecting family planning. Also, having many programs for the same thing can mean repeated work and uncoordinated services, leading to more forms and paperwork.

Popular music has changed a lot in the past 100 years. There are now many types of music. It is hard to name them all. Each type, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, has many smaller groups within it. Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most varied and expressive types in the last 40 years. It shows many feelings, often darker ones. It is diverse because people saw it could change. They made new styles from it. This led to even more new styles.

Today, heavy metal has many small groups. It is hard to say what heavy metal is now. It has mixed with other types of music. But, like all things, it started from something. To understand metal music today, we must know what the metal movement is and why it is a movement, not just a type of music.

Metal is a movement known for its dark side. It is a "music of more"—more bass, more noise, more intensity, more drama. Metal band members are skilled with their instruments, and it shows. Metal is also known for its link to drugs. In the mid-70s, many people used psychedelic drugs. This led them to make strange and intense music. Metal music has many dark qualities. This was new because much popular music was not dark. Later metal bands took ideas from the Romantic Era. The lyrics show the darkness that is key to metal.

Helter Skelter by The Beatles shows this dark side. It has ups and downs, like a drug experience. Some say it is one of the first Heavy Metal songs. The Beatles made it to show they could be as heavy as The Rolling Stones. They put it on The White Album.

Before the Surrealists painted dreamlike art, Henri Rousseau made his own dream paintings. His 1910 painting, The Dream, shows a woman amazed by the dream world she sees. This painting also shows Rousseau's dreams and hopes as a painter. From the start, he wanted other artists and art lovers to accept and praise him. He faced a hard choice to reach this goal. The Dream shows Rousseau's struggle: should he copy popular art styles to fit in, or be unique and follow his own way?

To understand The Dream, you need to know about Rousseau's life. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware seller. Rousseau had no formal art training. He worked for France in a toll service job until age forty. People wrongly called him a customs worker. His first wife, Clémence, died after losing eight babies, leaving him with one daughter, Julia. Full of sadness, Rousseau turned to painting for comfort and new hope. Unlike others who romanticized peasant life, he was a folk painter with simple hopes and dreams.

Rousseau wanted the art world to accept him. He had no formal training and started painting late. He also painted at the same time as famous artists. He got recognition only when Matisse was becoming known. In Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon says Matisse and Rousseau were different. Matisse feared being boring, while Rousseau wanted to paint in a way that would get him into Artiste Français.

Many smart people think there is a strong link between what is good and what is beautiful, between truth and beauty. I think there is a reason for this. In a poem, John Keats says, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty." We learn many things in life through school or experience. But we seem to understand what is good and what is beautiful, as Keats suggests, without being taught in these usual ways. Both ideas try to explain rather than tell us what to do. Our study of what is right and what is beautiful is mostly about why a piece of art or writing is good, or why an action is right, rather than rules for making good art or doing good things.

Also, talking about art or morals can never completely show what is truly good or beautiful. For example, when we talk about da Vinci's Mona Lisa, we might discuss things like the front, the back, how colors are used, or the culture it comes from. But these do not fully explain why it is good art. Often, when someone talks about their favorite art or book, they say, "There's just something about it," before giving a more detailed answer. I think art and morals can never be fully explained by their parts. As Flannery O'Connor says, a story is a way to say something that can't be said in any other way. Even if we describe all parts of a book, there is still something more. I think the same is true for what is right. Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I think this "something," this hard-to-explain quality, is the strongest part of both art and what is right. This makes a link between the two.

I think art and what is right are closely connected because we feel both deeply, even if we can't fully explain them. This link is even stronger in literature. McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality." Literature is important because of the values we find in it, just like in life.

Today, Germany is a strong and united country. It has a unique culture from the Alps in München to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This culture is also felt in Köln, on the river Rhine, through the center of Germany, and in the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Germany's culture comes from many different sources and tribes.

The ancestral land of the Germans is called Germania. The name's origin is debated by scholars. Tacitus said it came from a tribe called Tungrians, known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gauls. Julius Caesar first used “Germanus” in his writings on the Gallic Wars. He took the word from the Gauls to tell them apart from the tribes he had not conquered. Some think it meant "neighbor" in the Gaulish language. Caesar wrote about the Germans beyond the Rhine, who often fought the Gauls. Others say the name comes from the spear called a "ger" or from an Old Irish word meaning "to shout," showing Germans as loud.

Tacitus, a Roman historian, wrote about the Germans in AD 98. He believed they were native to their land and not mixed with others. He questioned why anyone would leave Asia, Africa, or Italy for Germany, with its harsh land and weather, unless it was their home.

Romans did not want to live in Germania. They sent expeditions for goods and fought sometimes, but they mostly returned to their empire. In the first century, Germanic tribes lived by the Roman Empire’s borders. They traded goods and served in the Roman army.

The play Twelfth Night suggests that while wearing a disguise can help deceive others for a long time, a person must eventually stop pretending. Otherwise, they might lose who they really are. Ending a deception is hard because it can make a person feel alone. So, a person must choose between keeping their true self or keeping their relationships with others. Some people may not mind being tricked, but others may get upset and feel hurt by the deception.

The issue of pretending to be the opposite gender is difficult. One important question is why someone would hide their true identity this way. For Viola, it is a form of protection. She says: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). Viola is in a strange place and thinks she must pretend to be a man to stay safe from danger. Her plan works, but it also cuts her off from the women who could support her. Also, she looks so much like a man that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her. Olivia says, “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Viola also has to deal with hidden feelings between her and Orsino, who says: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

To today’s readers, Twelfth Night may show how deception can reveal hidden feelings, especially for Olivia and Orsino. Some parts suggest these characters might have feelings they do not fully understand until Viola/Cesario makes them face these emotions. Is Olivia attracted to Cesario because she thinks Cesario is a man, or does she have feelings for women? It seems she does not, as Olivia easily switches her love from Cesario to Sebastian and sees Cesario/Viola as family: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

German rule in its colonies was often very harsh. This was clear in the killing of the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. But, not all of the German colonial empire was the same. Each colony had different ways of ruling and teaching. When the British took over German East Africa in 1919, they found many educated Africans. German schools in Kamerun and other places were also praised by writers of that time.

In South West Africa, it was different. Unlike East Africa, where the government started schools for Africans, education in South West Africa was mostly left to missions with little help from the government. The government spent a lot on education for Europeans there, building state schools and helping mission schools more. This led to long-term effects. While many Africans in other German colonies could read and write, most in South West Africa could not. Many reasons led to this difference. This paper will look at these reasons and focus on new studies about settler and government views on Africans.

There are many writings on education in German colonies. Most are in German and were written in the early 1900s. They mainly showed what the school systems were like. Later, English writings compared education in different German colonies and looked at details. These showed big differences in education between colonies. The most important study on this topic is by Cohen. Cohen looked at education in South West Africa and East Africa. He compared the school systems and explained why they were different. Cohen said that the large number of settlers in South West Africa was a key reason for its unique education system.

South West Africa had a better climate than other German colonies, though much of it was dry desert. By 1913, nearly 15,000 Europeans lived there. This was more than the 5,336 in East Africa, which had the next largest settler population.

The United States and Mexico are examples of two countries that had a long rivalry. This rivalry lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The main event in this rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. In this war, the United States attacked and defeated Mexico. The United States gained Texas and the American Southwest. There were many other clashes between the two countries. The rivalry slowed down just before the First World War. It began because Americans and Mexicans disagreed on religion, culture, and material interests.  

This is similar to many countries that have a rivalry with a neighbor. Countries that share a border often have clashes of interests. This can create rival positions between them. The United States and Mexico are like many other rivalries between countries that share a common border. David M. Pletcher says that only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting American diplomatic problems. Both of these countries are close to the United States. They have been rivals, while other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States.  

Religious issues caused a split between the two countries. This problem has affected many countries through history. Sally Frahm says that in the twentieth century, Americans opposed fascism and communism. In the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, they opposed Catholicism and monarchy. Like the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, there was an ideological struggle. But this struggle was about religious preferences, not political structure. The distrust came from the distrust between the English and Spanish. This feeling of distrust was a big obstacle in creating friendly relations between the United States and Mexico.  

Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes were about territorial issues and border raids from Mexico. There were also problems with outlaws from American border towns. This was a major problem until both countries used military force on their borders.  

Schmitt explains that the rivalry began to slow down as Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States. It ended when American goals changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the late 19th Century.

Fifteen years ago, I became disabled by an illness I never knew about. 

I was a nurse then. I chose this work because I needed safety and security. I did not have these as a child. People told me, "You will always find work because people always get sick." I heard this many times as I grew up. So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or a journalist, I chose nursing. 

But then, at 46 years old, I was single and had no money. I could not work. I am still disabled today. After 15 years on Social Security Disability, I have nothing that is mine. I get by, but every day is hard. My life is not sure anymore. But one thing is true: I could not have managed without my family and friends. Even strong people need help in hard times. 

Life will always have emergencies. There are no guarantees. No matter how prepared you are, some problems are too big to handle alone. 

I agree that people in the U.S. should not depend only on big government. It is not steady. But I think we should trust each other more. We should help each other and ask for help. We should not just build shelters alone. 

Conservatives in the U.S. talk about "rugged individualism." But what helped our ancestors was compassion, respect, and sharing. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies did not make it alone. 

So, be ready. I am ready. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water tablets, and plastic sheets. I have flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and canned foods. If you can grow and preserve your food, do it. It is a good idea. A wood stove is also good if you do not live in an apartment. 

But also, get to know your neighbors.

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born. One day, he would be called Buddha. During his life, he left the world and became wise. His teachings started Buddhism. The oldest form of Buddhism is Theravada Buddhism. This religion is about two thousand five hundred years old. It is different now than when Buddha was alive. You can see this in Sri Lanka, a Theravada country. There, people have a yearly water-cutting ceremony. Both monks and other people take part in it. This ceremony has some religious meaning, even though Buddha did not talk about such events. These changes are seen in both the simple traditions and the deep beliefs of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist group has changed its ideas over time. This is because of forces from both inside and outside, and some are good while others are not.

There are some terms we will use often. There is "internal" versus "external." An internal force comes from members of the Buddhasasana, whether they are monks or not. An external force is from people who are not Buddhists. A hostile force is one that harms or wants to harm Buddhists. A benign force does not want to hurt or help Buddhists, but it might do one of these by accident. We will talk about these terms often.

First, let us look at the main ideas of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find safety in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma includes the Tripitaka, which means three baskets of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka has the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka has rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has deep ideas like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (life is suffering), and Anicca (everything changes). By knowing these ideas, one can end Sansara, the cycle of birth and rebirth. When Sansara ends, so do lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion), when one becomes wise. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. For laymen, there are five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not behave badly in sex, and do not take drugs or alcohol. For monks, there are many more rules. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can end.
